I'm new to this dataset so I want to explore it a little. This is all I know so far:

Dataset Information

This is a transactional data set which contains all the transactions occurring between 01/12/2010 and 09/12/2011 for a UK-based and registered non-store online retail.The company mainly sells unique all-occasion gifts. Many customers of the company are wholesalers.

I know these are individual transactions. It looks like each transcation has an invoice number, a stock code related to the item sold, description, quantity, and unit price of the item sold, the purchasing customer, and the country of the transcation.

Now, I'll check for seasonality and sales trends over time.

In [18]:
# Create Recency, Frequency, and Monetary (RFM) features
import datetime as dt

# Define a reference date for recency calculation
reference_date = data['InvoiceDate'].max() + dt.timedelta(days=1)

# Aggregate data at the customer level
rfm = data.groupby('CustomerID').agg({
    'InvoiceDate': lambda x: (reference_date - x.max()).days,  # Recency
    'InvoiceNo': 'count',  # Frequency
    'Quantity': lambda x: (x * data.loc[x.index, 'UnitPrice']).sum()  # Monetary
}).rename(columns={'InvoiceDate': 'Recency', 'InvoiceNo': 'Frequency', 'Quantity': 'Monetary'})

# Display RFM dataset
rfm.head()

Step 6: Clustering with K-Means¶

In [20]:
# Determine the optimal number of clusters using the Elbow Method
inertia = []
for k in range(1, 15):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=512, n_init='auto')
    kmeans.fit(rfm_scaled)
    inertia.append(kmeans.inertia_)

# Plot the Elbow Curve
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
plt.plot(range(1, 15), inertia, marker='o')
plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters')
plt.ylabel('Inertia')
plt.title('Elbow Method')
plt.show()
In [21]:
# Fit K-Means with the optimal number of clusters
optimal_k = 7  # Replace this with the optimal number based on the elbow curve
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=optimal_k, random_state=512, n_init='auto')
rfm['Cluster'] = kmeans.fit_predict(rfm_scaled)

# Display cluster counts

# Plot each feature
features = ['Recency', 'Frequency', 'Monetary', 'Count']
for feature in features:
    cluster_summary[feature].plot(kind='bar', figsize=(10, 5), title=f"Cluster Analysis: {feature}", ylabel=feature)
    plt.show()

Cluster Descriptions Based on the Data¶

Cluster 0: Loyal High-Frequency Customers¶

  • Recency: 26.27 (active within the last month).
  • Frequency: 225.32 transactions (frequent shoppers).
  • Monetary: 8.39 (moderately high spenders).
  • Count: 716 customers.
  • Insights:
    • These are loyal customers who shop frequently and spend a significant amount.
  • Actionable Strategy:
    • Use loyalty programs and personalized promotions to retain and further engage these customers.

Cluster 1: Dormant Moderate Spenders¶

  • Recency: 178.60 (inactive for ~6 months).
  • Frequency: 40.06 transactions (moderate shopping frequency).
  • Monetary: 6.31 (moderate spenders).
  • Count: 603 customers.
  • Insights:
    • These customers are at risk of churn.
  • Actionable Strategy:
    • Reactivate them with targeted offers, such as discounts or email campaigns.

Cluster 2: VIP High-Spending Customers¶

  • Recency: 2.00 (very recently active).
  • Frequency: 5807.00 transactions (extremely frequent shoppers).
  • Monetary: 11.00 (very high spenders).
  • Count: 4 customers.
  • Insights:
    • These are your most valuable customers who contribute significantly to revenue.
  • Actionable Strategy:
    • Provide VIP treatment, such as exclusive services, personalized offers, and early access to products.

Cluster 3: Infrequent Low-Value Customers¶

  • Recency: 49.81 (somewhat recently active).
  • Frequency: 24.17 transactions (low shopping frequency).
  • Monetary: 5.45 (low spenders).
  • Count: 953 customers.
  • Insights:
    • These customers are low-value and shop infrequently.
  • Actionable Strategy:
    • Offer discounts or bundles to encourage more frequent shopping.

Cluster 4: Elite High-Frequency Customers¶

  • Recency: 8.72 (very recently active).
  • Frequency: 989.12 transactions (very frequent shoppers).
  • Monetary: 9.32 (high spenders).
  • Count: 50 customers.
  • Insights:
    • This elite group shops frequently and spends a significant amount.
  • Actionable Strategy:
    • Engage them with premium products, loyalty rewards, and exclusive promotions.

Cluster 5: Steady Moderate Spenders¶

  • Recency: 38.33 (active within the last month).
  • Frequency: 74.40 transactions (moderately frequent shoppers).
  • Monetary: 6.98 (moderate spenders).
  • Count: 1420 customers.
  • Insights:
    • These customers are consistent contributors to revenue.
  • Actionable Strategy:
    • Use seasonal offers and cross-sell opportunities to increase spending.

Cluster 6: Lapsed Low-Value Customers¶

  • Recency: 291.51 (inactive for ~10 months).
  • Frequency: 18.62 transactions (low shopping frequency).
  • Monetary: 5.35 (low spenders).
  • Count: 592 customers.
  • Insights:
    • These customers are at high risk of churn and contribute minimally to revenue.
  • Actionable Strategy:
    • Use strong incentives, such as deep discounts, to win them back.

Step 10: Insights and Recommendations¶

Key Observations¶

  1. Cluster 2 (VIP High-Spending Customers) and Cluster 4 (Elite High-Frequency Customers) are your most valuable groups. Focus on retention and rewarding their loyalty.
  2. Cluster 6 (Lapsed Low-Value Customers) and Cluster 1 (Dormant Moderate Spenders) are at risk of churn. Target them with reactivation campaigns.
  3. Cluster 0 (Loyal High-Frequency Customers) and Cluster 5 (Steady Moderate Spenders) are stable revenue contributors. Leverage cross-sell and upsell opportunities for these segments.
  4. Cluster 3 (Infrequent Low-Value Customers) has limited revenue potential but could be nudged to shop more often with discounts or incentives.
